hout sin. Michnik employs deep historical analysis and keen political observation in his insightful five-point philosophical meditation on morality in public life, ingeniously expounding on history, religion, moral thought, and the present political climate in his native country and throughout Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aJacobins. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPost-communismzPoland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aGrudzinska Gross, Irena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatynia, Elzbieta08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300207026423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300207026.jpg  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO